Barclays is to part company with PwC, its auditor for the past 120 years. The bank is pre-empting British and European regulations designed to shake up the audit market. PwC’s auditing of Barclays has come under the spotlight, with the Financial Reporting Council in December dropping a two-year inquiry into its compliance reports.
PwC has been Barclays’ auditor since 1896, when Price Waterhouse first signed off on the bank’s accounts, and the last tender was ten years ago. While Barclays’ audit committee was satisfied with the PwC’s performance, the bank’s annual report discloses that it will start a tender next year or in 2016 and that PwC will not be invited to take part.
